# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clickhouse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clickhouse/architecture] ClickHouse is a true column-oriented DBMS.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Data is stored by columns, and during the execution of arrays (vectors or chunks of columns).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Whenever possible, operations are dispatched on arrays, rather than on individual values.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is called "vectorized query execution" and it helps lower the cost of actual data processing.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It dates back to the `APL` (A programming language, 1957) and its descendants: `A +` (APL dialect), `J` (1990), `K` (1993), and `Q` (programming language from Kx Systems, 2003).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Array programming is used in scientific data processing.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Neither is this idea something new in relational databases.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, it is used in the `VectorWise` system (also known as Actian Vector Analytic Database by Actian Corporation).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are two different approaches for speeding up query processing: vectorized query execution and runtime code generation.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The latter removes all indirection and dynamic dispatch.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Neither of these approaches is strictly better than the other.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Runtime code generation can be better when it fuses many operations, thus fully utilizing CPU execution units and the pipeline.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Vectorized query execution can be less practical because it involves temporary vectors that must be written to the cache and read back.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] If the temporary data does not fit in the L2 cache, this becomes an issue.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But vectorized query execution more easily utilizes the SIMD capabilities of the CPU.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] A research paper written by our friends shows that it is better to combine both approaches.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] ClickHouse uses vectorized query execution and has limited initial support for runtime code generation.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `IColumn` interface is used to represent columns in memory (actually, chunks of columns).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This interface provides helper methods for the implementation of various relational operators.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Almost all operations are immutable: they do not modify the original column, but create a new modified one.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, the `IColumn :: filter` method accepts a filter byte mask.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is used for the `WHERE` and `HAVING` relational operators.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Additional examples: the `IColumn :: permute` method to support `ORDER BY`, the `IColumn :: cut` method to support `LIMIT`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Various `IColumn` implementations (`ColumnUInt8`, `ColumnString`, and so on) are responsible for the memory layout of columns.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The memory layout is usually a contiguous array.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For the integer type of columns, it is just one contiguous array, like `std :: vector`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For `String` and `Array` columns, it is two vectors: one for all array elements, placed contiguously, and a second one for offsets to the beginning of each array.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There is also `ColumnConst` that stores just one value in memory, but looks like a column.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Nevertheless, it is possible to work with individual values as well.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] To represent an individual value, the `Field` is used.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `Field` is just a discriminated union of `UInt64`, `Int64`, `Float64`, `String` and `Array`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `IColumn` has the `operator []` method to get the n-th value as a `Field`, and the `insert` method to append a `Field` to the end of a column.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] These methods are not very efficient, because they require dealing with temporary `Field` objects representing an individual value.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are more efficient methods, such as `insertFrom`, `insertRangeFrom`, and so on.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `Field` does not have enough information about a specific data type for a table.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, `UInt8`, `UInt16`, `UInt32`, and `UInt64` are all represented as `UInt64` in a `Field`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `IColumn` has methods for common relational transformations of data, but they do not meet all needs.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, `ColumnUInt64` does not have a method to calculate the sum of two columns, and `ColumnString` does not have a method to run a substring search.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] These countless routines are implemented outside of `IColumn`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Various functions on columns can be implemented in a generic, non-efficient way using `IColumn` methods to extract `Field` values, or in a specialized way using knowledge of inner memory layout of data in a specific `IColumn` implementation.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is implemented by casting functions to a specific `IColumn` type and deal with internal representation directly.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, `ColumnUInt64` has the `getData` method that returns a reference to an internal array, then a separate routine reads or fills that array directly.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] We have "leaky abstractions" to allow efficient specializations of various routines.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `IDataType` is responsible for serialization and deserialization: for reading and writing chunks of columns or individual values in binary or text form.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `IDataType` directly corresponds to data types in tables.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, there are `DataTypeUInt32`, `DataTypeDateTime`, `DataTypeString` and so on.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `IDataType` and `IColumn` are only loosely related to each other.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Different data types can be represented in memory by the same `IColumn` implementations.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, `DataTypeUInt32` and `DataTypeDateTime` are both represented by `ColumnUInt32` or `ColumnConstUInt32`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] In addition, the same data type can be represented by different `IColumn` implementations.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, `DataTypeUInt8` can be represented by `ColumnUInt8` or `ColumnConstUInt8`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For instance, `DataTypeUInt8` does not store anything at all (except virtual pointer `vptr`) and `DataTypeFixedString` stores just `N` (the size of fixed-size strings).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `IDataType` has helper methods for various data formats.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Examples are methods to serialize a value with possible quoting, to serialize a value for JSON, and to serialize a value as part of the XML format.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There is no direct correspondence to data formats.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, the different data formats `Pretty` and `TabSeparated` can use the same `serializeTextEscaped` helper method from the `IDataType` interface.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] A `Block` is a container that represents a subset (chunk) of a table in memory.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is just a set of triples: `(IColumn, IDataType, column name)`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] During query execution, data is processed by `Block`s.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] If we have a `Block`, we have data (in the `IColumn` object), we have information about its type (in `IDataType`) that tells us how to deal with that column, and we have the column name.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It could be either the original column name from the table or some artificial name assigned for getting temporary results of calculations.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] When we calculate some function over columns in a block, we add another column with its result to the block, and we do not touch columns for arguments of the function because operations are immutable.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Later, unneeded columns can be removed from the block, but not modified.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is convenient for the elimination of common subexpressions.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Blocks are created for every processed chunk of data.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Note that for the same type of calculation, the column names and types remain the same for different blocks, and only column data changes.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is better to split block data from the block header because small block sizes have a high overhead of temporary strings for copying shared_ptrs and column names.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] See the description at https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/blob/master/src/Processors/IProcessor.h.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Data formats are implemented with processors.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For byte-oriented input/output, there are `ReadBuffer` and `WriteBuffer` abstract classes.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] They are used instead of C++ `iostream`s.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Don't worry: every mature C++ project is using something other than `iostream`s for good reasons.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `ReadBuffer` and `WriteBuffer` are just a contiguous buffer and a cursor pointing to the position in that buffer.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Implementations may own or not own the memory for the buffer.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There is a virtual method to fill the buffer with the following data (for `ReadBuffer`) or to flush the buffer somewhere (for `WriteBuffer`).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are functions from `ReadHelpers` and `WriteHelpers` header files to help with formatting input/output.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, there are helpers to write a number in decimal format.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Let's examine what happens when you want to write a result set in `JSON` format to stdout.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] You have a result set ready to be fetched from a pulling `QueryPipeline`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] First, you create a `WriteBufferFromFileDescriptor(STDOUT_FILENO)` to write bytes to stdout.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Next, you connect the result from the query pipeline to `JSONRowOutputFormat`, which is initialized with that `WriteBuffer`, to write rows in `JSON` format to stdout.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This can be done via the `complete` method, which turns a pulling `QueryPipeline` into a completed `QueryPipeline`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Internally, `JSONRowOutputFormat` will write various JSON delimiters and call the `IDataType::serializeTextJSON` method with a reference to `IColumn` and the row number as arguments.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Consequently, `IDataType::serializeTextJSON` will call a method from `WriteHelpers.h`: for example, `writeText` for numeric types and `writeJSONString` for `DataTypeString`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The `IStorage` interface represents tables.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Different implementations of that interface are different table engines.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Examples are `StorageMergeTree`, `StorageMemory`, and so on.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Instances of these classes are just tables.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The key methods in `IStorage` are `read` and `write`, along with others such as `alter`, `rename`, and `drop`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The `read` method accepts the following arguments: a set of columns to read from a table, the `AST` query to consider, and the desired number of streams.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] In most cases, the read method is responsible only for reading the specified columns from a table, not for any further data processing.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] All subsequent data processing is handled by another part of the pipeline, which falls outside the responsibility of `IStorage`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The table's `read` method can return a `Pipe` consisting of multiple `Processors`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] These `Processors` can read from a table in parallel.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Then, you can connect these processors with various other transformations (such as expression evaluation or filtering), which can be calculated independently.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] And then, create a `QueryPipeline` on top of them, and execute it via `PipelineExecutor`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] These are functions that return a temporary `IStorage` object to use in the `FROM` clause of a query.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] To get a quick idea of how to implement your table engine, look at something simple, like `StorageMemory` or `StorageTinyLog`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] A hand-written recursive descent parser parses a query.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, `ParserSelectQuery` just recursively calls the underlying parsers for various parts of the query.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The `AST` is represented by nodes, which are instances of `IAST`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Interpreters are responsible for creating the query execution pipeline from an AST.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are simple interpreters, such as `InterpreterExistsQuery` and `InterpreterDropQuery`, as well as the more sophisticated `InterpreterSelectQuery`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The query execution pipeline is a combination of processors that can consume and produce chunks (sets of columns with specific types).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] A processor communicates via ports and can have multiple input ports and multiple output ports.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] A more detailed description can be found in src/Processors/IProcessor.h.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, the result of interpreting the `SELECT` query is a "pulling" `QueryPipeline` which has a special output port to read the result set from.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The result of the `INSERT` query is a "pushing" `QueryPipeline` with an input port to write data for insertion.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] And the result of interpreting the `INSERT SELECT` query is a "completed" `QueryPipeline` that has no inputs or outputs but copies data from `SELECT` to `INSERT` simultaneously.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `InterpreterSelectQuery` uses `ExpressionAnalyzer` and `ExpressionActions` machinery for query analysis and transformations.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This is where most rule-based query optimizations are performed.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `ExpressionAnalyzer` is quite messy and should be rewritten: various query transformations and optimizations should be extracted into separate classes to allow for modular transformations of the query.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] To address problems that exist in interpreters, a new `InterpreterSelectQueryAnalyzer` has been developed.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This is a new version of the `InterpreterSelectQuery`, which does not use the `ExpressionAnalyzer` and introduces an additional layer of abstraction between `AST` and `QueryPipeline`, called `QueryTree`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is fully ready for use in production, but just in case it can be turned off by setting the value of the `enable_analyzer` setting to `false`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are ordinary functions and aggregate functions.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For aggregate functions, see the next section.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Ordinary functions do not change the number of rows – they work as if they are processing each row independently.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] In fact, functions are not called for individual rows, but for `Block`'s of data to implement vectorized query execution.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are some miscellaneous functions, like blockSize, rowNumberInBlock, and runningAccumulate, that exploit block processing and violate the independence of rows.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] ClickHouse has strong typing, so there's no implicit type conversion.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] If a function does not support a specific combination of types, it throws an exception.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But functions can work (be overloaded) for many different combinations of types.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, the `plus` function (to implement the `+` operator) works for any combination of numeric types: `UInt8` + `Float32`, `UInt16` + `Int8`, and so on.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Also, some variadic functions can accept any number of arguments, such as the `concat` function.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Implementing a function may be slightly inconvenient because a function explicitly dispatches supported data types and supported `IColumns`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, the `plus` function has code generated by instantiation of a C++ template for each combination of numeric types, and constant or non-constant left and right arguments.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is an excellent place to implement runtime code generation to avoid template code bloat.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Also, it makes it possible to add fused functions like fused multiply-add or to make multiple comparisons in one loop iteration.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Due to vectorized query execution, functions are not short-circuited.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, if you write `WHERE f(x) AND g(y)`, both sides are calculated, even for rows, when `f(x)` is zero (except when `f(x)` is a zero constant expression).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But if the selectivity of the `f(x)` condition is high, and calculation of `f(x)` is much cheaper than `g(y)`, it's better to implement multi-pass calculation.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It would first calculate `f(x)`, then filter columns by the result, and then calculate `g(y)` only for smaller, filtered chunks of data.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Aggregate functions are stateful functions.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] They accumulate passed values into some state and allow you to get results from that state.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] They are managed with the `IAggregateFunction` interface.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] States can be rather simple (the state for `AggregateFunctionCount` is just a single `UInt64` value) or quite complex (the state of `AggregateFunctionUniqCombined` is a combination of a linear array, a hash table, and a `HyperLogLog` probabilistic data structure).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] States are allocated in `Arena` (a memory pool) to deal with multiple states while executing a high-cardinality `GROUP BY` query.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] States can have a non-trivial constructor and destructor: for example, complicated aggregation states can allocate additional memory themselves.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It requires some attention to creating and destroying states and properly passing their ownership and destruction order.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Aggregation states can be serialized and deserialized to pass over the network during distributed query execution or to write them on the disk where there is not enough RAM.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] They can even be stored in a table with the `DataTypeAggregateFunction` to allow incremental aggregation of data.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Internally, it is just a primitive multithread server without coroutines or fibers.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Since the server is not designed to process a high rate of simple queries but to process a relatively low rate of complex queries, each of them can process a vast amount of data for analytics.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The server initializes the `Context` class with the necessary environment for query execution: the list of available databases, users and access rights, settings, clusters, the process list, the query log, and so on.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] We maintain full backward and forward compatibility for the server TCP protocol: old clients can talk to new servers, and new clients can talk to old servers.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But we do not want to maintain it eternally, and we are removing support for old versions after about one year.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For most external applications, we recommend using the HTTP interface because it is simple and easy to use.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The TCP protocol is more tightly linked to internal data structures: it uses an internal format for passing blocks of data, and it uses custom framing for compressed data.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] ClickHouse Server is based on POCO C++ Libraries and uses `Poco::Util::AbstractConfiguration` to represent its configuration.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Configuration is held by `Poco::Util::ServerApplication` class inherited by `DaemonBase` class, which in turn is inherited by `DB::Server` class, implementing clickhouse-server itself.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] So config can be accessed by `ServerApplication::config()` method.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Config is read from multiple files (in XML or YAML format) and merged into single `AbstractConfiguration` by `ConfigProcessor` class.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Configuration is loaded at server startup and can be reloaded later if one of config files is updated, removed or added.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `ConfigReloader` class is responsible for periodic monitoring of these changes and reload procedure as well.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `SYSTEM RELOAD CONFIG` query also triggers config to be reloaded.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For queries and subsystems other than `Server` config is accessible using `Context::getConfigRef()` method.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Every subsystem that is capable of reloading its config without server restart should register itself in reload callback in `Server::main()` method.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Note that if newer config has an error, most subsystems will ignore new config, log warning messages and keep working with previously loaded config.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Due to the nature of `AbstractConfiguration` it is not possible to pass reference to specific section, so `String config_prefix` is usually used instead.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Background operations can be configured via global and 'background' profile settings; session and query settings have no effect in this case.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] If no explicit configuration given, the configuration will inherit from global context.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The default profile name for such operations is 'background', which can be overridden via `background_profile` server setting.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] To execute queries and do side activities ClickHouse allocates threads from one of thread pools to avoid frequent thread creation and destruction.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Server pool is a `Poco::ThreadPool` class instance defined in `Server::main()` method.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It can have at most `max_connection` threads.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Every thread is dedicated to a single active connection.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Global thread pool is `GlobalThreadPool` singleton class.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] To allocate thread from it `ThreadFromGlobalPool` is used.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It has an interface similar to `std::thread`, but pulls thread from the global pool and does all necessary initialization.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Global pool is universal and all pools described below are implemented on top of it.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This can be thought of as a hierarchy of pools.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Any specialized pool takes its threads from the global pool using `ThreadPool` class.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] So the main purpose of any specialized pool is to apply limit on the number of simultaneous jobs and do job scheduling.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] If there are more jobs scheduled than threads in a pool, `ThreadPool` accumulates jobs in a queue with priorities.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] All jobs with higher priority values are started before any job with lower priority value.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But there is no difference between already executing jobs, thus priority matters only when the pool in overloaded.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] IO thread pool is implemented as a plain `ThreadPool` accessible via `IOThreadPool::get()` method.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It is configured in the same way as global pool with `max_io_thread_pool_size`, `max_io_thread_pool_free_size` and `io_thread_pool_queue_size` settings.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The main purpose of IO thread pool is to avoid exhaustion of the global pool with IO jobs, which could prevent queries from fully utilizing CPU.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Backup to S3 does significant amount of IO operations and to avoid impact on interactive queries there is a separate `BackupsIOThreadPool` configured with `max_backups_io_thread_pool_size`, `max_backups_io_thread_pool_free_size` and `backups_io_thread_pool_queue_size` settings.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For periodic task execution there is `BackgroundSchedulePool` class.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] You can register tasks using `BackgroundSchedulePool::TaskHolder` objects and the pool ensures that no task runs two jobs at the same time.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It also allows you to postpone task execution to a specific instant in the future or temporarily deactivate task.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Global `Context` provides a few instances of this class for different purposes.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For general purpose tasks `Context::getSchedulePool()` is used.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are also specialized thread pools for preemptable tasks.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Such `IExecutableTask` task can be split into ordered sequence of jobs, called steps.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] To schedule these tasks in a manner allowing short tasks to be prioritized over long ones `MergeTreeBackgroundExecutor` is used.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] As name suggests it is used for background MergeTree related operations such as merges, mutations, fetches and moves.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Pool instances are available using `Context::getCommonExecutor()` and other similar methods.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] No matter what pool is used for a job, at start `ThreadStatus` instance is created for this job.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It encapsulates all per-thread information: thread id, query id, performance counters, resource consumption and many other useful data.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Job can access it via thread local pointer by `CurrentThread::get()` call, so we do not need to pass it to every function.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] If thread is related to query execution, then the most important thing attached to `ThreadStatus` is query context `ContextPtr`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Every query has its master thread in the server pool.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Master thread does the attachment by holding an `ThreadStatus::QueryScope query_scope(query_context)` object.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Master thread also creates a thread group represented with `ThreadGroupStatus` object.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Every additional thread that is allocated during this query execution is attached to its thread group by `CurrentThread::attachTo(thread_group)` call.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Thread groups are used to aggregate profile event counters and track memory consumption by all threads dedicated to a single task (see `MemoryTracker` and `ProfileEvents::Counters` classes for more information).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Query that can be parallelized uses `max_threads` setting to limit itself.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Default value for this setting is selected in a way that allows single query to utilize all CPU cores in the best way.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But what if there are multiple concurrent queries and each of them uses default `max_threads` setting value?
[src:clickhouse/architecture] OS will ensure fairness by constantly switching threads, which introduce some performance penalty.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `ConcurrencyControl` helps to deal with this penalty and avoid allocating a lot of threads.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Configuration setting `concurrent_threads_soft_limit_num` is used to limit how many concurrent thread can be allocated before applying some kind of CPU pressure.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Slot is a unit of concurrency: to run a thread query has to acquire a slot in advance and release it when thread stops.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The number of slots is globally limited in a server.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Multiple concurrent queries are competing for CPU slots if the total demand exceeds the total number of slots.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `ConcurrencyControl` is responsible to resolve this competition by doing CPU slot scheduling in a fair manner.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Note that `allocated` slot can be in two different states: `granted` and `acquired`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The former is a transitional state, that actually should be short (from the instant when a slot is allocated to a query till the moment when the up-scaling procedure is run by any thread of that query).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For every thread a slot has to be acquired from an allocation: `while (auto slot = slots->tryAcquire()) spawnThread([slot = std::move(slot)] { ... });`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Update the total amount of slots: `ConcurrencyControl::setMaxConcurrency(concurrent_threads_soft_limit_num)`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Can be done in runtime, w/o server restart.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This API allows queries to start with at least one thread (in presence of CPU pressure) and later scale up to `max_threads`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Servers in a cluster setup are mostly independent.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] You can create a `Distributed` table on one or all servers in a cluster.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The `Distributed` table does not store data itself – it only provides a "view" to all local tables on multiple nodes of a cluster.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] When you SELECT from a `Distributed` table, it rewrites that query, chooses remote nodes according to load balancing settings, and sends the query to them.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The `Distributed` table requests remote servers to process a query just up to a stage where intermediate results from different servers can be merged.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Then it receives the intermediate results and merges them.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The distributed table tries to distribute as much work as possible to remote servers and does not send much intermediate data over the network.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Things become more complicated when you have subqueries in IN or JOIN clauses, and each of them uses a `Distributed` table.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] We have different strategies for the execution of these queries.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There is no global query plan for distributed query execution.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Each node has its local query plan for its part of the job.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] We only have simple one-pass distributed query execution: we send queries for remote nodes and then merge the results.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But this is not feasible for complicated queries with high cardinality `GROUP BY`s or with a large amount of temporary data for JOIN.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] In such cases, we need to "reshuffle" data between servers, which requires additional coordination.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] ClickHouse does not support that kind of query execution, and we need to work on it.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `MergeTree` is a family of storage engines that supports indexing by primary key.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The primary key can be an arbitrary tuple of columns or expressions.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Data in a `MergeTree` table is stored in "parts".
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Each part stores data in the primary key order, so data is ordered lexicographically by the primary key tuple.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] All the table columns are stored in separate `column.bin` files in these parts.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Each block is usually from 64 KB to 1 MB of uncompressed data, depending on the average value size.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The blocks consist of column values placed contiguously one after the other.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Column values are in the same order for each column (the primary key defines the order), so when you iterate by many columns, you get values for the corresponding rows.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] It does not address every single row, but only some ranges of data.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] A separate `primary.idx` file has the value of the primary key for each N-th row, where N is called `index_granularity` (usually, N = 8192).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Also, for each column, we have `column.mrk` files with "marks", which are offsets to each N-th row in the data file.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Each mark is a pair: the offset in the file to the beginning of the compressed block, and the offset in the decompressed block to the beginning of data.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Usually, compressed blocks are aligned by marks, and the offset in the decompressed block is zero.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Data for `primary.idx` always resides in memory, and data for `column.mrk` files is cached.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] When we are going to read something from a part in `MergeTree`, we look at `primary.idx` data and locate ranges that could contain requested data, then look at `column.mrk` data and calculate offsets for where to start reading those ranges.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Because of sparseness, excess data may be read.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] ClickHouse is not suitable for a high load of simple point queries, because the entire range with `index_granularity` rows must be read for each key, and the entire compressed block must be decompressed for each column.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] We made the index sparse because we must be able to maintain trillions of rows per single server without noticeable memory consumption for the index.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Also, because the primary key is sparse, it is not unique: it cannot check the existence of the key in the table at INSERT time.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] You could have many rows with the same key in a table.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] When you `INSERT` a bunch of data into `MergeTree`, that bunch is sorted by primary key order and forms a new part.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are background threads that periodically select some parts and merge them into a single sorted part to keep the number of parts relatively low.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Of course, merging leads to "write amplification".
[src:clickhouse/architecture] All parts are immutable: they are only created and deleted, but not modified.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] When SELECT is executed, it holds a snapshot of the table (a set of parts).
[src:clickhouse/architecture] After merging, we also keep old parts for some time to make a recovery after failure easier, so if we see that some merged part is probably broken, we can replace it with its source parts.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] `MergeTree` is not an LSM tree because it does not contain MEMTABLE and LOG: inserted data is written directly to the filesystem.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This behavior makes MergeTree much more suitable to insert data in batches.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Therefore, frequently inserting small amounts of rows is not ideal for MergeTree.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, a couple of rows per second is OK, but doing it a thousand times a second is not optimal for MergeTree.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] However, there is an async insert mode for small inserts to overcome this limitation.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There are MergeTree engines that are doing additional work during background merges.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Examples are `CollapsingMergeTree` and `AggregatingMergeTree`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This could be treated as special support for updates.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Keep in mind that these are not real updates because users usually have no control over the time when background merges are executed, and data in a `MergeTree` table is almost always stored in more than one part, not in completely merged form.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Replication in ClickHouse can be configured on a per-table basis.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] You could have some replicated and some non-replicated tables on the same server.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] You could also have tables replicated in different ways, such as one table with two-factor replication and another with three-factor.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Replication is implemented in the `ReplicatedMergeTree` storage engine.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The path in `ZooKeeper` is specified as a parameter for the storage engine.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] All tables with the same path in `ZooKeeper` become replicas of each other: they synchronize their data and maintain consistency.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Replicas can be added and removed dynamically simply by creating or dropping a table.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Replication uses an asynchronous multi-master scheme.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] You can insert data into any replica that has a session with `ZooKeeper`, and data is replicated to all other replicas asynchronously.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Because ClickHouse does not support UPDATEs, replication is conflict-free.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] As there is no quorum acknowledgment of inserts by default, just-inserted data might be lost if one node fails.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The insert quorum can be enabled using `insert_quorum` setting.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Metadata for replication is stored in ZooKeeper.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] There is a replication log that lists what actions to do.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Actions are: get part; merge parts; drop a partition, and so on.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Each replica copies the replication log to its queue and then executes the actions from the queue.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] For example, on insertion, the "get the part" action is created in the log, and every replica downloads that part.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Merges are coordinated between replicas to get byte-identical results.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] All parts are merged in the same way on all replicas.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] One of the leaders initiates a new merge first and writes "merge parts" actions to the log.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Multiple replicas (or all) can be leaders at the same time.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] A replica can be prevented from becoming a leader using the `merge_tree` setting `replicated_can_become_leader`.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The leaders are responsible for scheduling background merges.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Replication is physical: only compressed parts are transferred between nodes, not queries.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Merges are processed on each replica independently in most cases to lower the network costs by avoiding network amplification.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Large merged parts are sent over the network only in cases of significant replication lag.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Besides, each replica stores its state in ZooKeeper as the set of parts and its checksums.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] When the state on the local filesystem diverges from the reference state in ZooKeeper, the replica restores its consistency by downloading missing and broken parts from other replicas.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] When there is some unexpected or broken data in the local filesystem, ClickHouse does not remove it, but moves it to a separate directory and forgets it.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The ClickHouse cluster consists of independent shards, and each shard consists of replicas.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] The cluster is **not elastic**, so after adding a new shard, data is not rebalanced between shards automatically.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] Instead, the cluster load is supposed to be adjusted to be uneven.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] This implementation gives you more control, and it is ok for relatively small clusters, such as tens of nodes.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] But for clusters with hundreds of nodes that we are using in production, this approach becomes a significant drawback.
[src:clickhouse/architecture] We should implement a table engine that spans across the cluster with dynamically replicated regions that could be split and balanced between clusters automatically.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] ClickHouse, Inc. was incorporated in San Francisco, California, in September 2021 to commercialize the open-source ClickHouse database.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] The company was initially funded with US$50 million from Index Ventures and Benchmark Capital, with participation from Yandex N.V. and others.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] On 28 October 2021, the company announced a US$250 million Series B funding round at a valuation of US$2 billion, led by Coatue Management, Altimeter Capital, and others.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] The round valued the company at approximately US$6.35 billion and brought total funding to more than US$650 million.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] The company continues to build and maintain the open source project in parallel to a cloud-based offering.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] ClickHouse’s technology was first developed at Yandex, Russia's largest technology company.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] In 2009, Alexey Milovidov and developers started an experimental project to check the hypothesis if it was viable to generate analytical reports in real-time from non-aggregated data that is also constantly added in real-time.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] The developers spent 3 years to prove this hypothesis, and in 2012 ClickHouse launched in production for the first time to power Yandex.Metrica.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] In 2016, the ClickHouse project was released as open-source software under the Apache 2 license to power analytical use cases around the globe.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] The systems at the time offered a server throughput of a hundred thousand rows per second, while ClickHouse provided a throughput of hundreds of millions of rows per second.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] Since ClickHouse became available as open source in 2016, its popularity has grown, as evidenced through adoption by industry-leading companies like Uber, Comcast, eBay, and Cisco.
[src:clickhouse/clickhouse] ClickHouse was also implemented at CERN's LHCb experiment to store and process metadata on 10 billion events with over 1000 attributes per event.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:clickhouse/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] In a real column-oriented DBMS, no extra data is stored with the values.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] This means that constant-length values must be supported to avoid storing their length "number" next to the values.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] For example, a billion UInt8-type values should consume around 1 GB uncompressed, or this strongly affects the CPU use.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] It is essential to store data compactly (without any "garbage") even when uncompressed since the speed of decompression (CPU usage) depends mainly on the volume of uncompressed data.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] This is in contrast to systems that can store values of different columns separately, but that can't effectively process analytical queries due to their optimization for other scenarios, such as HBase, Bigtable, Cassandra, and Hypertable.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] You would get throughput of around a hundred thousand rows per second in these systems, but not hundreds of millions of rows per second.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Finally, ClickHouse is a database management system, not a single database.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] It allows creating tables and databases in runtime, loading data, and running queries without reconfiguring and restarting the server.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Some column-oriented DBMSs don't use data compression.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] However, data compression plays a key role in achieving excellent performance.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] In addition to efficient general-purpose compression codecs with different trade-offs between disk space and CPU consumption, ClickHouse provides specialized codecs for specific kinds of data, which allows ClickHouse to compete with and outperform more niche databases, like time-series ones.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Keeping data physically sorted by primary key makes it possible to extract data based on specific values or value ranges with low latency in less than a few dozen milliseconds.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Some column-oriented DBMSs, such as SAP HANA and Google PowerDrill, can only work in RAM.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] This approach requires allocation of a larger hardware budget than necessary for real-time analysis.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] ClickHouse is designed to work on regular hard drives, which means the cost per GB of data storage is low, but SSD and additional RAM are also fully used if available.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Large queries are parallelized naturally, taking all the necessary resources available on the current server.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Almost none of the columnar DBMSs mentioned above have support for distributed query processing.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] In ClickHouse, data can reside on different shards.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Each shard can be a group of replicas used for fault tolerance.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] All shards are used to run a query in parallel, transparently for the user.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] ClickHouse supports a declarative query language based on SQL that is mostly compatible with the ANSI SQL standard.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Supported queries include GROUP BY, ORDER BY, subqueries in FROM, the JOIN clause, the IN operator, window functions and scalar subqueries.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Correlated (dependent) subqueries aren't supported at the time of writing but might become available in the future.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Data isn't only stored by columns but is processed by vectors (parts of columns), which allows achieving high CPU efficiency.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] ClickHouse supports tables with a primary key.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] To quickly perform queries on the range of the primary key, the data is sorted incrementally using the merge tree.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Due to this, data can continually be added to the table.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] No locks are taken when new data is ingested.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Having data physically sorted by primary key makes it possible to extract data based on specific values or value ranges with low latency in less than a few dozen milliseconds.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Unlike other database management systems, secondary indexes in ClickHouse don't point to specific rows or row ranges.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Instead, they allow the database to know in advance that all rows in some data parts wouldn't match the query filtering conditions and don't read them at all, thus they're called data skipping indexes.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Most OLAP database management systems don't aim for online queries with sub-second latencies.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] In alternative systems, report building time of tens of seconds or even minutes is often considered acceptable.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Sometimes it takes even more time, which forces systems to prepare reports offline (in advance or by responding with "come back later").
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] In ClickHouse, "low latency" means that queries can be processed without delay and without trying to prepare an answer in advance, right at the moment when the user interface page is loading — in other words, *online*.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Running a query based on a part (SAMPLE) of data and getting an approximated result.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] In this case, proportionally less data is retrieved from the disk.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Running an aggregation for a limited number of random keys, instead of for all keys.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Under certain conditions for key distribution in the data, this provides a reasonably accurate result while using fewer resources.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] ClickHouse adaptively chooses how to JOIN multiple tables, by preferring hash join and falling back to merge join if there's more than one large table.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] ClickHouse uses asynchronous multi-master replication.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] After being written to any available replica, all the remaining replicas retrieve their copy in the background.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] The system maintains identical data on different replicas.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Recovery after most failures is performed automatically, or semi-automatically in complex cases.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] For more information, see the section Data replication.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] ClickHouse implements user account management using SQL queries and allows for role-based access control configuration similar to what can be found in the ANSI SQL standard and popular relational database management systems.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] Lack of ability to modify or delete already inserted data with a high rate and low latency.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] There are batch deletes and updates available to clean up or modify data, for example, to comply with GDPR.
[src:clickhouse/distinctive-features] The sparse index makes ClickHouse not so efficient for point queries retrieving single rows by their keys.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse® is a high-performance, column-oriented SQL database management system (DBMS) for online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:clickhouse/intro] It is available as both an open-source software and a cloud offering.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Analytics, also known as OLAP (Online Analytical Processing), refers to SQL queries with complex calculations (e.g., aggregations, string processing, arithmetic) over massive datasets.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Unlike transactional queries (or OLTP, Online Transaction Processing) that read and write just a few rows per query and, therefore, complete in milliseconds, analytics queries routinely process billions and trillions of rows.
[src:clickhouse/intro] In many use cases, analytics queries must be "real-time", i.e., return a result in less than one second.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Such a level of performance can only be achieved with the right data "orientation".
[src:clickhouse/intro] Databases store data either row-oriented or column-oriented.
[src:clickhouse/intro] In a row-oriented database, consecutive table rows are sequentially stored one after the other.
[src:clickhouse/intro] This layout allows to retrieve rows quickly as the column values of each row are stored together.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse is a column-oriented database.
[src:clickhouse/intro] In such systems, tables are stored as a collection of columns, i.e. the values of each column are stored sequentially one after the other.
[src:clickhouse/intro] This layout makes it harder to restore single rows (as there are now gaps between the row values) but column operations such as filters or aggregation become much faster than in a row-oriented database.
[src:clickhouse/intro] As you can see in the stats section in the above diagram, the query processed 100 million rows in 92 milliseconds, a throughput of approximately over 1 billion rows per second or just under 7 GB of data transferred per second.
[src:clickhouse/intro] In a row-oriented database, even though the query above only processes a few out of the existing columns, the system still needs to load the data from other existing columns from disk to memory.
[src:clickhouse/intro] The reason for that is that data is stored on disk in chunks called blocks (usually fixed sizes, e.g., 4 KB or 8 KB).
[src:clickhouse/intro] Blocks are the smallest units of data read from disk to memory.
[src:clickhouse/intro] When an application or database requests data, the operating system's disk I/O subsystem reads the required blocks from the disk.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Because the values of each column are stored sequentially one after the other on disk, no unnecessary data is loaded when the query from above is run.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Because the block-wise storage and transfer from disk to memory is aligned with the data access pattern of analytical queries, only the columns required for a query are read from disk, avoiding unnecessary I/O for unused data.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse uses an asynchronous multi-master replication scheme to ensure that data is stored redundantly on multiple nodes.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse implements user account management using SQL queries and allows for role-based access control configuration similar to what can be found in ANSI SQL standard and popular relational database management systems.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse supports a declarative query language based on SQL that is identical to the ANSI SQL standard in many cases.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Supported query clauses include GROUP BY, ORDER BY, subqueries in FROM, JOIN clause, IN operator, window functions and scalar subqueries.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse provides ways to trade accuracy for performance.
[src:clickhouse/intro] For example, some of its aggregate functions calculate the distinct value count, the median, and quantiles approximately.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Also, queries can be run on a sample of the data to compute an approximate result quickly.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Finally, aggregations can be run with a limited number of keys instead of for all keys.
[src:clickhouse/intro] Depending on how skewed the distribution of the keys is, this can provide a reasonably accurate result that uses far fewer resources than an exact calculation.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse chooses the join algorithm adaptively: it starts with fast hash joins and falls back to merge joins if there's more than one large table.
[src:clickhouse/intro] ClickHouse is well known for having extremely fast query performance.
[src:clickhouse/intro] To learn why ClickHouse is so fast, see the Why is ClickHouse fast? guide.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `MergeTree` engine and other engines of the `MergeTree` family (e.g.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `ReplacingMergeTree`, `AggregatingMergeTree` ) are the most commonly used and most robust table engines in ClickHouse.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `MergeTree`-family table engines are designed for high data ingest rates and huge data volumes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Insert operations create table parts which are merged by a background process with other table parts.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Main features of `MergeTree`-family table engines.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Despite a similar name, the Merge engine is different from `*MergeTree` engines.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `ENGINE` — Name and parameters of the engine.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `MergeTree` engine has no parameters.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] A tuple of column names or arbitrary expressions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Example: `ORDER BY (CounterID + 1, EventDate)`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `PRIMARY KEY` was not specified), ClickHouse uses the sorting key as primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If no sorting is required, you can use syntax `ORDER BY tuple()`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Alternatively, if setting `create_table_empty_primary_key_by_default` is enabled, `ORDER BY ()` is implicitly added to `CREATE TABLE` statements.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In most cases, you don't need a partition key, and if you do need to partition, generally you do not need a partition key more granular than by month.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Partitioning does not speed up queries (in contrast to the ORDER BY expression).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] You should never use too granular partitioning.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Don't partition your data by client identifiers or names (instead, make client identifier or name the first column in the ORDER BY expression).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For partitioning by month, use the `toYYYYMM(date_column)` expression, where `date_column` is a column with a date of the type Date.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The partition names here have the `"YYYYMM"` format.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `PRIMARY KEY` — The primary key if it differs from the sorting key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Specifying a sorting key (using `ORDER BY` clause) implicitly specifies a primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] It is usually not necessary to specify the primary key in addition to the sorting key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If specified, it must be contained in the primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The sampling expression must result in an unsigned integer.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Example: `SAMPLE BY intHash32(UserID) ORDER BY (CounterID, EventDate, intHash32(UserID))`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `TTL` — A list of rules that specify the storage duration of rows and the logic of automatic parts movement between disks and volumes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Expression must result in a `Date` or `DateTime`, e.g.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Default type of the rule is removal (`DELETE`).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] List of multiple rules can be specified, but there should be no more than one `DELETE` rule.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In the example, we set partitioning by month.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] We also set an expression for sampling as a hash by the user ID.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] This allows you to pseudorandomize the data in the table for each `CounterID` and `EventDate`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If you define a SAMPLE clause when selecting the data, ClickHouse will return an evenly pseudorandom data sample for a subset of users.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `index_granularity` setting can be omitted because 8192 is the default value.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If possible, switch old projects to the method described above.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `MergeTree` engine is configured in the same way as in the example above for the main engine configuration method.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] A table consists of data parts sorted by primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] When data is inserted in a table, separate data parts are created and each of them is lexicographically sorted by primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For example, if the primary key is `(CounterID, Date)`, the data in the part is sorted by `CounterID`, and within each `CounterID`, it is ordered by `Date`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Data belonging to different partitions are separated into different parts.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In the background, ClickHouse merges data parts for more efficient storage.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Parts belonging to different partitions are not merged.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The merge mechanism does not guarantee that all rows with the same primary key will be in the same data part.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Data parts can be stored in `Wide` or `Compact` format.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In `Wide` format each column is stored in a separate file in a filesystem, in `Compact` format all columns are stored in one file.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `Compact` format can be used to increase performance of small and frequent inserts.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Data storing format is controlled by the `min_bytes_for_wide_part` and `min_rows_for_wide_part` settings of the table engine.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If the number of bytes or rows in a data part is less then the corresponding setting's value, the part is stored in `Compact` format.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Otherwise it is stored in `Wide` format.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If none of these settings is set, data parts are stored in `Wide` format.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Each data part is logically divided into granules.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] A granule is the smallest indivisible data set that ClickHouse reads when selecting data.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ClickHouse does not split rows or values, so each granule always contains an integer number of rows.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The first row of a granule is marked with the value of the primary key for the row.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For each data part, ClickHouse creates an index file that stores the marks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For each column, whether it's in the primary key or not, ClickHouse also stores the same marks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] These marks let you find data directly in column files.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The granule size is restricted by the `index_granularity` and `index_granularity_bytes` settings of the table engine.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The number of rows in a granule lays in the `[1, index_granularity]` range, depending on the size of the rows.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The size of a granule can exceed `index_granularity_bytes` if the size of a single row is greater than the value of the setting.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In this case, the size of the granule equals the size of the row.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Take the `(CounterID, Date)` primary key as an example.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The examples above show that it is always more effective to use an index than a full scan.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] A sparse index allows extra data to be read.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] When reading a single range of the primary key, up to `index_granularity * 2` extra rows in each data block can be read.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Sparse indexes allow you to work with a very large number of table rows, because in most cases, such indexes fit in the computer's RAM.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ClickHouse does not require a unique primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] You can insert multiple rows with the same primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] You can use `Nullable`-typed expressions in the `PRIMARY KEY` and `ORDER BY` clauses but it is strongly discouraged.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] To allow this feature, turn on the allow_nullable_key setting.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The NULLS_LAST principle applies for `NULL` values in the `ORDER BY` clause.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The number of columns in the primary key is not explicitly limited.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Depending on the data structure, you can include more or fewer columns in the primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] A long primary key will negatively affect the insert performance and memory consumption, but extra columns in the primary key do not affect ClickHouse performance during `SELECT` queries.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] You can create a table without a primary key using the `ORDER BY tuple()` syntax.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In this case, ClickHouse stores data in the order of inserting.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If you want to save data order when inserting data by `INSERT ...
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] SELECT` queries, set max_insert_threads = 1.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] To select data in the initial order, use single-threaded `SELECT` queries.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] It is possible to specify a primary key (an expression with values that are written in the index file for each mark) that is different from the sorting key (an expression for sorting the rows in data parts).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In this case the primary key expression tuple must be a prefix of the sorting key expression tuple.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] This feature is helpful when using the SummingMergeTree and AggregatingMergeTree table engines.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In a common case when using these engines, the table has two types of columns: *dimensions* and *measures*.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Typical queries aggregate values of measure columns with arbitrary `GROUP BY` and filtering by dimensions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Because SummingMergeTree and AggregatingMergeTree aggregate rows with the same value of the sorting key, it is natural to add all dimensions to it.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] As a result, the key expression consists of a long list of columns and this list must be frequently updated with newly added dimensions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In this case it makes sense to leave only a few columns in the primary key that will provide efficient range scans and add the remaining dimension columns to the sorting key tuple.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ALTER of the sorting key is a lightweight operation because when a new column is simultaneously added to the table and to the sorting key, existing data parts do not need to be changed.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Since the old sorting key is a prefix of the new sorting key and there is no data in the newly added column, the data is sorted by both the old and new sorting keys at the moment of table modification.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For `SELECT` queries, ClickHouse analyzes whether an index can be used.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Thus, it is possible to quickly run queries on one or many ranges of the primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In this example, queries will be fast when run for a specific tracking tag, for a specific tag and date range, for a specific tag and date, for multiple tags with a date range, and so on.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ClickHouse will use the primary key index to trim improper data and the monthly partitioning key to trim partitions that are in improper date ranges.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The queries above show that the index is used even for complex expressions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Reading from the table is organized so that using the index can't be slower than a full scan.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In the example below, the index can't be used.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] To check whether ClickHouse can use the index when running a query, use the settings force_index_by_date and force_primary_key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The key for partitioning by month allows reading only those data blocks which contain dates from the proper range.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In this case, the data block may contain data for many dates (up to an entire month).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Within a block, data is sorted by primary key, which might not contain the date as the first column.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Because of this, using a query with only a date condition that does not specify the primary key prefix will cause more data to be read than for a single date.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The primary key can contain expressions, not only column names.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] These expressions are not limited to simple function chains: they can be arbitrary expression trees (for example, nested functions and composite expressions), as long as they are deterministic.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] An expression is **deterministic** if it always returns the same result for the same input values (for example: `length()`, `toDate()`, `lower()`, `left()`, `cityHash64()`, `toUUID()`; unlike `now()` or `rand()`).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If the primary key contains deterministic expressions, ClickHouse can apply them to constant values from the query and use the result to build conditions on the primary key index.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] This enables data skipping for predicates like `=`, `IN`, and `has`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] A common use case is to keep the primary key compact (e.g. store a hash instead of a long `String`), while still allowing predicates on the original column to use the index.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In these cases, ClickHouse computes `length('alice')` (and other constants) once and uses the length values to narrow the ranges in the primary key index.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Since length of a string is **not injective**, different `user_id` strings can share the same length, so the index may read extra granules (false positives).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The result remains correct because the original predicate (`user_id = ...`, `IN`, etc.) is still applied after reading.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If the deterministic expression is also **injective** (different inputs cannot produce the same output for the argument types used), additionally ClickHouse can effectively use the index for the negated forms: `!=`, `NOT IN`, and `NOT has(...)`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For example, `reverse(p)` and `hex(p)` are injective for `String`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Consider, for example, the days of the month.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] They form a monotonic sequence for one month, but not monotonic for more extended periods.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If a user creates the table with partially-monotonic primary key, ClickHouse creates a sparse index as usual.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] When a user selects data from this kind of table, ClickHouse analyzes the query conditions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If the user wants to get data between two marks of the index and both these marks fall within one month, ClickHouse can use the index in this particular case because it can calculate the distance between the parameters of a query and index marks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ClickHouse cannot use an index if the values of the primary key in the query parameter range do not represent a monotonic sequence.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In this case, ClickHouse uses the full scan method.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ClickHouse uses this logic not only for days of the month sequences, but for any primary key that represents a partially-monotonic sequence.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The index declaration is in the columns section of the `CREATE` query.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For tables from the `*MergeTree` family, data skipping indices can be specified.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] These indices aggregate some information about the specified expression on blocks, which consist of `granularity_value` granules (the size of the granule is specified using the `index_granularity` setting in the table engine).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Then these aggregates are used in `SELECT` queries for reducing the amount of data to read from the disk by skipping big blocks of data where the `where` query cannot be satisfied.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `GRANULARITY` clause can be omitted, the default value of `granularity_value` is 1.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `MergeTree` table engine supports the following types of skip indexes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For more information on how skip indexes can be used for performance optimization see "Understanding ClickHouse data skipping indexes".
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For each index granule, the minimum and maximum values of an expression are stored.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For each index granule at most `max_rows` many unique values of the specified expression are stored.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `max_rows = 0` means "store all unique values".
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For each index granule stores a bloom filter for the specified columns.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `false_positive_rate` parameter can take on a value between 0 and 1 (by default: `0.025`) and specifies the probability of generating a positive (which increases the amount of data to be read).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For the `Map` data type, the client can specify if the index should be created for keys or for values using the `mapKeys` or `mapValues` functions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For the `JSON` data type, a bloom filter index can be created on the set of paths using the `JSONAllPaths` function.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] This allows skipping granules where a queried JSON path is absent.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] See Data skipping indexes for JSON for details.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] With general availability (GA) of the `text` index starting from ClickHouse version 26.2, the `ngrambf_v1` index is no longer recommended for full text search.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] See page "Full-text search with text indexes" for details.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For each index granule stores a bloom filter for the n-grams of the specified columns.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] To estimate the parameters of `ngrambf_v1`, you can use the following User Defined Functions (UDFs).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For example, there are `4300` ngrams in the granule and you expect false positives to be less than `0.0001`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Of course, you can also use those functions to estimate parameters for other conditions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The functions above refer to the bloom filter calculator here.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] With general availability (GA) of the `text` index starting from ClickHouse version 26.2, the `tokenbf_v1` index is no longer recommended for full text search.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The sparse grams bloom filter is similar to `ngrambf_v1` but uses sparse grams tokens instead of ngrams.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Builds an inverted index over tokenized string data, enabling efficient and deterministic full-text search.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Supports approximate nearest neighbor search, see here for details.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Conditions in the `WHERE` clause contains calls of the functions that operate with columns.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If the column is a part of an index, ClickHouse tries to use this index when performing the functions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ClickHouse supports different subsets of functions for using indexes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Indexes of type `set` can be utilized by all functions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Functions with a constant argument that is less than ngram size can't be used by `ngrambf_v1` for query optimization.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] (*) For `hasTokenCaseInsensitive` and `hasTokenCaseInsensitiveOrNull` to be effective, the `tokenbf_v1` index must be created on lowercased data, for example `INDEX idx (lower(str_col)) TYPE tokenbf_v1(512, 3, 0)`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Bloom filters can have false positive matches, so the `ngrambf_v1`, `tokenbf_v1`, `sparse_grams`, and `bloom_filter` indexes can not be used for optimizing queries where the result of a function is expected to be false.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Projections are like materialized views but defined in part-level.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] It provides consistency guarantees along with automatic usage in queries.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] When you are implementing projections you should also consider the force_optimize_projection setting.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Projections are not supported in the `SELECT` statements with the FINAL modifier.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] A projection query is what defines a projection.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] It implicitly selects data from the parent table.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Projections can be modified or dropped with the ALTER statement.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Projection indexes extend the projection subsystem by providing a lightweight and explicit way to define projection-level indexes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Externally, a projection index is still a projection, but with simplified syntax and clearer intent: it defines an expression which is dedicated to filtering, rather than serving materialized data.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Internally, a projection index does not materialize the original table in permuted row order like a regular projection.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Instead, the permutation is stored in the form of a numeric permutation column `_part_offset`, i.e.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `SELECT _part_offset ORDER BY <index_expr>`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The framework allows adding more index types in the future.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Projections are stored inside the part directory.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] It's similar to an index but contains a subdirectory that stores an anonymous `MergeTree` table's part.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The table is induced by the definition query of the projection.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If there is a `GROUP BY` clause, the underlying storage engine becomes AggregatingMergeTree, and all aggregate functions are converted to `AggregateFunction`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If there is an `ORDER BY` clause, the `MergeTree` table uses it as its primary key expression.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] During the merge process the projection part is merged via its storage's merge routine.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The checksum of the parent table's part is combined with the projection's part.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Other maintenance jobs are similar to skip indices.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Select the best feasible match, which contains the least granules to read.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The query pipeline which uses projections will be different from the one that uses the original parts.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If the projection is absent in some parts, we can add the pipeline to "project" it on the fly.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For concurrent table access, we use multi-versioning.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In other words, when a table is simultaneously read and updated, data is read from a set of parts that is current at the time of the query.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Inserts do not get in the way of read operations.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Reading from a table is automatically parallelized.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `TTL` clause can be set for the whole table and for each individual column.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Table-level `TTL` can also specify the logic of automatic moving data between disks and volumes, or recompressing parts where all the data has been expired.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Expressions must evaluate to Date, Date32, DateTime or DateTime64 data type.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] TTL is evaluated during background merges, and not at insert time.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Functions like `rand()`, `now()`, or `now64()` will be re-evaluated on every merge, leading to unpredictable deletion behavior.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] ClickHouse blocks expressions with no column dependency at all, but does not currently reject non-deterministic functions mixed with a column reference (e.g.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] TTL expressions should be based solely on deterministic, column-derived values for predictable results.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] When the values in the column expire, ClickHouse replaces them with the default values for the column data type.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If all the column values in the data part expire, ClickHouse deletes this column from the data part in a filesystem.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] The `TTL` clause can't be used for key columns.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Table can have an expression for removal of expired rows, and multiple expressions for automatic move of parts between disks or volumes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] When rows in the table expire, ClickHouse deletes all corresponding rows.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] For parts moving or recompressing, all rows of a part must satisfy the `TTL` expression criteria.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Type of TTL rule may follow each TTL expression.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] `GROUP BY` expression must be a prefix of the table primary key.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If a column is not part of the `GROUP BY` expression and is not set explicitly in the `SET` clause, in result row it contains an occasional value from the grouped rows (as if aggregate function `any` is applied to it).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Creating a table, where the rows are expired after one month.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Creating a table, where expired rows are aggregated.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] In result rows `x` contains the maximum value across the grouped rows, `y` — the minimum value, and `d` — any occasional value from grouped rows.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] Data with an expired `TTL` is removed when ClickHouse merges data parts.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] When ClickHouse detects that data is expired, it performs an off-schedule merge.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] To control the frequency of such merges, you can set `merge_with_ttl_timeout`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If the value is too low, it will perform many off-schedule merges that may consume a lot of resources.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] If you perform the `SELECT` query between merges, you may get expired data.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p01] To avoid it, use the OPTIMIZE query before `SELECT`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] `MergeTree` family table engines can store data on multiple block devices.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] For example, it can be useful when the data of a certain table are implicitly split into "hot" and "cold".
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The most recent data is regularly requested but requires only a small amount of space.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] On the contrary, the fat-tailed historical data is requested rarely.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] If several disks are available, the "hot" data may be located on fast disks (for example, NVMe SSDs or in memory), while the "cold" data - on relatively slow ones (for example, HDD).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] This applies to all disk types, including S3 and other object storage disks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] For example, you can spread data across multiple S3 buckets within a single volume, or create tiered policies that move data from local disks to S3.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] See Using S3 disks with multiple volumes for details.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Data part is the minimum movable unit for `MergeTree`-engine tables.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The data belonging to one part are stored on one disk.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Data parts can be moved between disks in the background (according to user settings) as well as by means of the ALTER queries.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The names given to the described entities can be found in the system tables, system.storage_policies and system.disks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] To apply one of the configured storage policies for a table, use the `storage_policy` setting of `MergeTree`-engine family tables.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Disks, volumes and storage policies should be declared inside the `<storage_configuration>` tag either in a file in the `config.d` directory.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Disks can also be declared in the `SETTINGS` section of a query.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] This is useful for ad-hoc analysis to temporarily attach a disk that is, for example, hosted at a URL.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The order of the disk definition is not important.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] In given example, the `hdd_in_order` policy implements the round-robin approach.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Thus this policy defines only one volume (`single`), the data parts are stored on all its disks in circular order.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Such policy can be quite useful if there are several similar disks are mounted to the system, but RAID is not configured.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Keep in mind that each individual disk drive is not reliable and you might want to compensate it with replication factor of 3 or more.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] If there are different kinds of disks available in the system, `moving_from_ssd_to_hdd` policy can be used instead.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The volume `hot` consists of an SSD disk (`fast_ssd`), and the maximum size of a part that can be stored on this volume is 1GB.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] All the parts with the size larger than 1GB will be stored directly on the `cold` volume, which contains an HDD disk `disk1`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Also, once the disk `fast_ssd` gets filled by more than 80%, data will be transferred to the `disk1` by a background process.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The order of volume enumeration within a storage policy is important in case at least one of the volumes listed has no explicit `volume_priority` parameter.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Once a volume is overfilled, data are moved to the next one.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The order of disk enumeration is important as well because data are stored on them in turns.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The `default` storage policy implies using only one volume, which consists of only one disk given in `<path>`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] You could change storage policy after table creation with [ALTER TABLE ...
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] MODIFY SETTING] query, new policy should include all old disks and volumes with same names.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The number of threads performing background moves of data parts can be changed by background_move_pool_size setting.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Within this volume, that disk is chosen that follows the one, which was used for storing the previous chunk of data, and that has free space more than the part size (`unreserved_space - keep_free_space_bytes > current_part_size`).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Under the hood, mutations and partition freezing make use of hard links.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Hard links between different disks are not supported, therefore in such cases the resulting parts are stored on the same disks as the initial ones.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] In the background, parts are moved between volumes on the basis of the amount of free space (`move_factor` parameter) according to the order the volumes are declared in the configuration file.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Data is never transferred from the last one and into the first one.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] One may use system tables system.part_log (field `type = MOVE_PART`) and system.parts (fields `path` and `disk`) to monitor background moves.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Also, the detailed information can be found in server logs.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] User can force moving a part or a partition from one volume to another using the query ALTER TABLE ...
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] TO VOLUME|DISK ..., all the restrictions for background operations are taken into account.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] The query initiates a move on its own and does not wait for background operations to be completed.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] User will get an error message if not enough free space is available or if any of the required conditions are not met.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Moving data does not interfere with data replication.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Therefore, different storage policies can be specified for the same table on different replicas.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] After the completion of background merges and mutations, old parts are removed only after a certain amount of time (`old_parts_lifetime`).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] During this time, they are not moved to other volumes or disks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Therefore, until the parts are finally removed, they are still taken into account for evaluation of the occupied disk space.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] User can assign new big parts to different disks of a JBOD volume in a balanced way using the min_bytes_to_rebalance_partition_over_jbod setting.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] MergeTree family table engines can store data to `S3`, `AzureBlobStorage`, `HDFS` using a disk with types `s3`, `azure_blob_storage`, `hdfs` accordingly.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] See configuring external storage options for more details.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Example for S3 as external storage using a disk with type `s3`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Also see configuring external storage options.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] S3 (and other object storage) disks can be used in multi-disk and multi-volume storage policies the same way as local disks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] This allows you to spread data across multiple S3 buckets within a single volume (JBOD-style), or set up tiered storage policies with S3 volumes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] When using `use_environment_credentials` for S3 authentication, the environment credentials (`AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID`, `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY`, `AWS_SESSION_TOKEN`) are shared across all S3 disks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] It is not possible to use different environment credentials for different disks.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] If you need different credentials for each S3 disk, use explicit `access_key_id` and `secret_access_key` settings per disk instead.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] It is possible to set up non-replicated MergeTree tables with a one-writer, many-readers scenario on shared storage.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] This is provided by the automatic refresh of the parts list, which can be set up on readers.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Note that this requires shared filesystem metadata across replicas (or `table_disk = true` with a table-local disk).
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] See refresh_parts_interval and table_disk.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] ClickHouse versions 22.3 through 22.7 use a different cache configuration, see using local cache if you are using one of those versions.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] These lightweight statistics aggregate information about distribution of values in columns.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Statistics are stored in every part and updated when every insert comes.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] They can be used for prewhere optimization only if we enable `set use_statistics = 1`.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] When `use_statistics_for_part_pruning` is enabled, statistics can be used for part pruning.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Currently, only `MinMax` and `Basic` statistics support part pruning.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] When such statistics are defined on a column, ClickHouse tracks the minimum and maximum values for that column in each part.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] Part pruning allows to skip reading entire data parts when the query filter condition cannot match any rows in that part.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] All of the above also accept `Nullable` and `LowCardinality(Nullable)` wrappers of the listed types.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] `Basic` may additionally be declared on `Nullable` wrappers of types like `UUID` or `IPv6` purely to track the null count.
[src:clickhouse/mergetree-family-mergetree-p02] For `Basic` on `String` / `FixedString` columns the statistic only records the total non-NULL byte length (used to estimate average string length) and the null count; range filters and part pruning are not driven by it.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:clickhouse/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
